      <h1>W-2 vs. W-4 Tax Forms: What is the Difference?</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 23, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Tax forms can be confusing. Two of the most common forms you will encounter in your career are W-2 and W-4. Here is a clear breakdown of the differences and how they impact your finances.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Quick summary:</strong> You fill out a <strong>W-4 form</strong> when you start a job to tell your employer how much tax to withhold. Your employer sends you a <strong>W-2 form</strong> in January showing how much you earned and how much tax was actually withheld.</div>

      <h2>What is a W-4 form?</h2>
      <p>A W-4 form (Employee's Withholding Certificate) is filled out by you, the employee. You submit it to your employer when you start a new job, or whenever you experience a major life event (like marriage or having a child) that changes your tax situation.</p>
      <p>The information you provide on your W-4—including filing status, dependents, and any additional withholding amounts—tells your employer's payroll department how much federal income tax to deduct from each paycheck. Filling it out accurately prevents you from owing money at tax time or receiving a massive, interest-free refund that could have been in your monthly budget.</p>

      <h2>What is a W-2 form?</h2>
      <p>A W-2 form (Wage and Tax Statement) is filled out by your employer. They are legally required to send this form to you and the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) by January 31st of each year, detailing your earnings from the previous calendar year.</p>
      <p>Your W-2 lists your total wages, tips, and other compensation, as well as the exact amounts deducted for federal income tax, state income tax, Social Security, and Medicare. You use the information on your W-2 to file your annual tax return.</p>

